stdyInfo.abstract: Since 1985, the training programme for Young Researchers (hereinafter referred to as the YR programme) has been implemented in various forms in Slovenia. The programme focuses on the education of prospective students, who are recognized as the bearers of the development of science and for which the state, therefore, devotes considerable funds. The starting point of the research was to examine how the YR programme accomplishes its goal of building a knowledge society The main purpose was to examine knowledge implementation in practice to determine whether the invested public funds are reimbursed to the society in the long run. Three focus groups and a survey were carried out to analyze the program. The additional objectives of the study were to highlight examples of good practices and areas where the program could be further improved.

sumDscr.universe: 1) All individuals who (from the beginning of the program up to the academic year 2010/2011) were at any time included in the training programme for Young Researchers (MR) and Young Researchers from the Economy (MRG) in Slovenia, regardless of whether the training was at that time already completed, still ongoing or was terminated early. The number of all units in the population is 6264, the list was provided by ARRS (MR) and TIA (MRG). The final sample includes the list of people with an active e-mail account (3763).

2) All individuals who (from the beginning of the program up to the academic year 2010/2011) were at any time included in the training programme for Young Researchers (MR) and Young Researchers from the Economy (MRG) in Slovenia, regardless of whether the training was at that time already completed, still ongoing or was terminated early. The number of all units in the population is 6264, the list was provided by ARRS (MR) and TIA (MRG). The final sample includes the list of people with an active e-mail account (3763). Mentors of young researchers participated in one focus group.
1) Individuals for whom it was not possible to obtain an e-mail address (n=2501).

dataColl.collSitu: 1) Web survey. Respondents received an e-mail link to the questionnaire in the LimeSurvey web application, together with detailed instructions for completing and definitions of important concepts used in questionnaire. The completion of the survey questionnaire lasted approximately 15 minutes.

2) Young researchers were invited to the focus group at the end of the survey questionnaire, mentors were called upon subsequently. Due to the high level of non-response, additional participants for the focus groups were recruited via social networks, using the snowball method. About 50 people were contacted, of which the final sample was 17. Focus groups lasted approximately two hours and were recorded and transcribed.
